<subSubSection box="[151,523,1057,1083]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,523,1057,1083]" box="[151,523,1057,1083]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,523,1057,1083]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,523,1057,1083]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<taxonomicName authority="Brown" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,380,1057,1083]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,1057,1083]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
Brown
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[393,523,1057,1083]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" rank="genus">new genus</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="206" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,971,1124,1150]" box="[151,971,1124,1150]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<typeStatus box="[151,201,1126,1150]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Brown" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" box="[294,588,1125,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[294,510,1125,1149]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia floridana</emphasis>
Brown
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[598,723,1124,1149]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[598,723,1124,1149]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, by present designation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1195,2014]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<emphasis box="[151,279,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
is proposed for three species formerly placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Razowski, 1967" authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[855,1180,1195,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[855,983,1196,1222]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Spinipogon</emphasis>
Razowski, 1967
</taxonomicName>
, i.e., 
<taxonomicName authority="(Razowski, 1967)" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski" baseAuthorityYear="1967" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinifera" status="new combination">
<emphasis box="[1246,1377,1196,1222]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">P. spinifera</emphasis>
(Razowski, 1967)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[322,525,1231,1258]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[322,525,1231,1258]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" rank="species">new combination</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="(Razowski and Becker 1986)" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski and Becker" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[540,1049,1231,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="veracruzanus" status="new combination">
<emphasis box="[540,717,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">P. veracruzanus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O." box="[731,1041,1231,1258]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" pagination="441 - 500" refId="ref21108" refString="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O. (1986) Cochylidii (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) collected in Central America and Mexico. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 29, 441 - 500." type="journal article" year="1986">Razowski and Becker 1986</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1059,1263,1231,1258]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1059,1263,1231,1258]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" rank="species">new combination</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
; and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Razowski, 1967)" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski" baseAuthorityYear="1967" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signata" status="new combination">
<emphasis box="[1324,1341,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1354,1436,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">signata</emphasis>
(Razowski, 1967)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[365,569,1267,1294]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[365,569,1267,1294]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" rank="species">new combination</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
; and one new species described herein. The last is from southern 
<collectingRegion box="[1308,1389,1267,1293]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Florida</collectingRegion>
and appears to be the only 
<collectingCountry box="[410,460,1304,1330]" name="United States of America" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">U.S.</collectingCountry>
representative of 
<emphasis box="[665,793,1304,1329]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Razowski, J." box="[808,1001,1303,1330]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" pagination="121 - 320" refId="ref20987" refString="Razowski, J. (1994) Synopsis of the Neotropical Cochylini (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae). Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 37, 121 - 320." type="journal article" year="1994">Razowski (1994)</bibRefCitation>
referred to “two groups of species…” in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[182,310,1340,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[182,310,1340,1366]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Spinipogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which I recognize as distinct genera. Although 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[866,996,1340,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinifera">
<emphasis box="[866,996,1340,1366]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">P. spinifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski and Becker" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[1011,1191,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="veracruzanus">
<emphasis box="[1011,1191,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">P. veracruzanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the new species are convincingly associated by male genitalia, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[682,796,1376,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signata">
<emphasis box="[682,699,1376,1401]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[714,796,1376,1401]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">signata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the female, and its genitalia are not like those of any other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[418,546,1412,1438]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[418,546,1412,1438]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Spinipogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Females of most (but not all) species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[1026,1154,1412,1438]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1026,1154,1412,1438]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Spinipogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1212,1340,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
have an unusual and characteristic spiny, truncate-cone-shaped process emanating from the corpus bursae (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O." pageId="11" pageNumber="206" pagination="421 - 464" refId="ref21076" refString="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O. (1983) Brazilian Cochylidii (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae). Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 26, 421 - 464." type="journal article" year="1983">Razowski and Becker 1983</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 111, 112), similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Le Marchand" authorityYear="1933" box="[723,847,1484,1510]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Phalonidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[723,847,1484,1510]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Phalonidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Turner, 1916" authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="1916" box="[902,1239,1483,1510]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Gynnidomorpha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[902,1086,1484,1510]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Gynnidomorpha</emphasis>
Turner, 1916
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1195,2014]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
The male genitalia of the species included in 
<emphasis box="[713,841,1520,1545]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
are very similar, however, they can be distinguished most easily by the shape of the median process of the transtilla. 
<bibRefCitation author="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O." box="[873,1201,1555,1582]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" pagination="441 - 500" refId="ref21108" refString="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O. (1986) Cochylidii (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) collected in Central America and Mexico. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 29, 441 - 500." type="journal article" year="1986">Razowski and Becker (1986)</bibRefCitation>
provided three illustrations of the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski and Becker" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[513,693,1592,1618]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="veracruzanus">
<emphasis box="[513,693,1592,1618]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">S. veracruzanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, all from Estación Biologia Las Tuxtlas in 
<collectingRegion box="[1181,1284,1592,1618]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1295,1383,1591,1617]" name="Mexico" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, and recognized two different “forms” which mostly likely represent different species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="207" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1195,2014]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1437,153,1151]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="207" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1663,1690]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Superficially, adults of 
<emphasis box="[591,719,1664,1689]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[734,800,1663,1690]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1832,1857]" captionTargetBox="[194,1394,166,1812]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[192,1396,166,1812]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Adults of Cochylini genera. 1. Anacochylidia maderana, Madera Canyon, Santa Rita Mountains, Arizona (EME). 2. Cagiva cephalanthana, Dorman Lake, Oktibbeha Co., Mississippi (USNM). 3. Atroposia oenotherana, Houston, Harris Co., Texas (USNM). 4. Atroposia oenotherana, Radisson, Onondaga Co., New York (USNM). 5. Cybilla hubbardana, Shafter, Presidio Co., Texas (USNM). 6. Cybilla hubbardana, Lordsburg, Hidalgo Co., New Mexico (CNC). 7. Honca grandis, Chimney Gulch, Golden, Colorado (USNM). 8. Pogospinia floridana, Long Key State Park, Monroe Co., Florida (USNM). 9. Nycthia pimama, Portal, Cochise Co., Arizona (USNM). 10. Nycthia yuccatana, Falcon State Park, Starr Co., Texas (USNM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442348/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[1070,1198,1664,1690]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1070,1198,1664,1690]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Spinipogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Busck, 1939" authorityName="Busck" authorityYear="1939" box="[1212,1432,1663,1690]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Lorita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1212,1282,1664,1689]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Lorita</emphasis>
Busck, 1939
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1829" box="[151,249,1700,1726]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Cochylis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,249,1700,1726]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Cochylis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1897" box="[266,375,1700,1726]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Thyraylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[266,375,1700,1726]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Thyraylia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and others, however, they usually are slightly smaller. The male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1259,1344,1699,1726]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–26" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1861,1886]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1805]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,174,1805]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 19–26. Male genitalia of Cochylini genera. 19. Anacochylidia maderana, Palmerlee, Arizona, USNM slide 23,359. 20. Atroposia oenotherana, Padre Island National Seashore, Texas, USNM slide 153,596. 21. Cagiva cephalanthana, Dorman Lake, Mississippi, USNM slide 150,530. 22. Cybilla hubbardana, Tucson, Arizona, USNM slide 29,397. 23. Honca grandis, Ogden Canyon, Utah, USNM slide 153,598. 24. Nycthia pimama, Blair Valley, California, USNM slide 144,042. 25. Nycthia yuccatana, Laguna Atacosa, Texas, USNM slide 120,405. 26. Pogospinia floridana, Key Largo, Florida, USNM slide 23,249." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442352/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
) of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
are easily distinguished by the shape of the valva: the distal 0.3–0.5 is widely bifurcate with a broad, round- ed or squarish concavity between the termination of the costa and the termination of the ventral edge (sacculus) (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 19–26" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1861,1886]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1805]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,174,1805]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 19–26. Male genitalia of Cochylini genera. 19. Anacochylidia maderana, Palmerlee, Arizona, USNM slide 23,359. 20. Atroposia oenotherana, Padre Island National Seashore, Texas, USNM slide 153,596. 21. Cagiva cephalanthana, Dorman Lake, Mississippi, USNM slide 150,530. 22. Cybilla hubbardana, Tucson, Arizona, USNM slide 29,397. 23. Honca grandis, Ogden Canyon, Utah, USNM slide 153,598. 24. Nycthia pimama, Blair Valley, California, USNM slide 144,042. 25. Nycthia yuccatana, Laguna Atacosa, Texas, USNM slide 120,405. 26. Pogospinia floridana, Key Largo, Florida, USNM slide 23,249." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442352/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
; also see 
<bibRefCitation author="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O." box="[288,581,1807,1834]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" pagination="441 - 500" refId="ref21108" refString="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O. (1986) Cochylidii (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) collected in Central America and Mexico. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 29, 441 - 500." type="journal article" year="1986">Razowski &amp; Becker 1986</bibRefCitation>
: figs 103‒108). This shape is unique among Cochylina and distinguishes the three described species of 
<emphasis box="[452,580,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
for which males are known. 
<emphasis box="[914,1042,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
appears to be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[181,309,1880,1906]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[181,309,1880,1906]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Spinipogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the two genera share similar socii, a similar median process of the transtilla, and fused arms of the vinculum, sometimes forming a weak saccus. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[707,835,1916,1942]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[707,835,1916,1942]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Spinipogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the valva are somewhat rectangular or parallel-sided and not bifurcate distally (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O." box="[490,801,1951,1977]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" pagination="441 - 500" refId="ref21108" refString="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O. (1986) Cochylidii (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) collected in Central America and Mexico. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 29, 441 - 500." type="journal article" year="1986">Razowski and Becker 1986</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 109, 110; 
<bibRefCitation author="Razowski, J." box="[979,1157,1951,1978]" pageId="11" pageNumber="206" pagination="161 - 181" refId="ref20959" refString="Razowski, J. (1993) Cochylini (Lepidoptera, Tortricidae) from Peru and Bolivia. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 36, 161 - 181." type="journal article" year="1993">Razowski 1993</bibRefCitation>
: figs 33, 34; 
<bibRefCitation author="Metzler, E. &amp; Sabourin, M." pageId="11" pageNumber="206" pagination="69 - 76" refId="ref20280" refString="Metzler, E. &amp; Sabourin, M. (2002) A new species of Spinipogon Razowski, 1967 from two remnant prairies in Ohio (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae, Cochylini). Fabreries, 27, 69 - 76." type="journal article" year="2002">Metzler and Sabourin 2002</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 2a, b). The absence of cornuti in the vesica of 
<emphasis box="[917,1045,1988,2013]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="206">Pogospinia</emphasis>
is shared with a few other genera, including 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[264,392,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,392,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Spinipogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Males of 
<emphasis box="[511,639,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Pogospinia</emphasis>
lack both a forewing costal fold a hindwing costal roll.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="207" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,1151]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,188,215]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Description</emphasis>
. Head: Frons and vertex rough scaled; ocellus present; sensory setae of antenna 0.8–1.0 times flagellomere diameter in male, shorter in female; labial palpus porrect, length of all segments combined 1.0–1.2 times diameter of compound eye, segment III weakly exposed; maxillary palpus 1-segmented. Thorax: Posterior crest weak; lateral scales of metanotum hairlike. Forewing length 
<quantity box="[878,1011,296,323]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.9" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.3" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" unit="mm" value="3.9" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="3.3">3.3–4.5 mm</quantity>
in male, 
<quantity box="[1111,1245,296,323]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.45" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="4.4" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" unit="mm" value="4.45" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="4.4">4.4–4.5 mm</quantity>
in female, length 2.5–2.9 times maximum width, slightly wider in female; costa gently arched from base, apex round, male without costal fold; termen straight, oblique; Sc ca. 0.5 wing length; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[856,864,386,400]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</subScript>
originating near middle of discal cell; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1324,1332,386,400]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">2</subScript>
originating nearer R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[291,299,422,436]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">3</subScript>
than R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[382,390,422,436]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</subScript>
; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[425,433,422,436]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">5</subScript>
ending at costa; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[652,660,422,436]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[769,777,422,436]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</subScript>
separate; CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[945,953,422,436]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">2</subScript>
originating about 0.6 length of discal cell; CuP absent; A1+2 stalked at 0.4 length. Hindwing length 2.5–3.6 times width; costa straight, male without costal roll; apex rounded; termen concave between M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[692,700,494,508]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[784,792,494,508]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">2</subScript>
; Sc+R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[871,879,494,508]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</subScript>
about 0.6 wing length; Rs and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1268,1276,494,508]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</subScript>
stalked about 0.4 length of M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[325,333,530,544]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</subScript>
; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[372,380,530,544]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[488,496,530,544]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</subScript>
separate; CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[662,670,530,544]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">2</subScript>
originating 0.65 length of discal cell; frenulum with one acanthus in male, two in female. Abdomen: Unmodified. Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[847,930,549,576]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–26" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1861,1886]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,174,1805]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,174,1805]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 19–26. Male genitalia of Cochylini genera. 19. Anacochylidia maderana, Palmerlee, Arizona, USNM slide 23,359. 20. Atroposia oenotherana, Padre Island National Seashore, Texas, USNM slide 153,596. 21. Cagiva cephalanthana, Dorman Lake, Mississippi, USNM slide 150,530. 22. Cybilla hubbardana, Tucson, Arizona, USNM slide 29,397. 23. Honca grandis, Ogden Canyon, Utah, USNM slide 153,598. 24. Nycthia pimama, Blair Valley, California, USNM slide 144,042. 25. Nycthia yuccatana, Laguna Atacosa, Texas, USNM slide 120,405. 26. Pogospinia floridana, Key Largo, Florida, USNM slide 23,249." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442352/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
) with uncus absent; socius rounded, broadly attached to top of tegumen, setose; transtilla well developed, median process variable from short and blunt to bifurcate, spined or minutely dentate; valva wide at base, bifurcate in distal 0.5‒0.7 with dorsal (costal) lobe and ventral (sacculus) lobe, each with well-developed field of strong spines; vinculum arms fused distally forming V-shaped saccus. Phallus large, slender, 0.8–1.3 times length of valva, pointed apically; vesica without cornuti. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[194,275,729,755]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–43" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[228,1358,166,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[228,1359,166,1890]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 39–43. Female genitalia of Cochylini genera. 39. Nycthia yuccatana, Laguna Atacosa, Texas, USNM slide 150,135. 40. Pogospinia floridana, Archbold Biological Station, Florida, USNM slide 23,216. 41. Cochylichroa atricapitana, Germany, USNM slide 153,638. 42. Monoceratuncus lantana, Fremont, Texas, USNM slide 23,056. 43. Mimcochylis fulvotinctana, Huachuca Mountains, Arizona, USNM slide 153,591." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442358" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442358/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
) with papillae anales weakly lobate, setose; length of apophyses anteriores ca. 0.8 times that of apophyses posteriores, apophyses anteriores connected to sclerotized sterigma; sterigma variable from complicated with dense patches of spiculation, and rounded V-shaped median process to simple with median sclerite; ductus bursae short, with colliculumlike sclerotized band, weakly differentiated from corpus bursae; corpus bursae variable, round to elongate, with minute spicules and a truncate-cone-shaped process of long spines; accessory bursa originating from anterior third of corpus bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="207" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,1151]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,490,944,971]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Distribution and biology</emphasis>
. The genus ranges from 
<collectingCountry box="[764,832,945,971]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[848,975,945,971]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinifera">
<emphasis box="[848,975,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">P. spinifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) north through 
<collectingCountry box="[1148,1234,945,971]" name="Mexico" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Razowski and Becker" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[1249,1427,946,971]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="veracruzanus">
<emphasis box="[1249,1427,946,971]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">P. veracruzanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) to Florida; it likely occurs in the Caribbean. Little is known of the life history of 
<emphasis box="[1054,1182,982,1007]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Pogospinia</emphasis>
, however, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" box="[1305,1436,981,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Pogospinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis box="[1305,1436,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">P. floridana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reared (n = 3 individuals) by Don Davis from 
<taxonomicName box="[731,1020,1017,1043]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Anthernanthera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maritima">
<emphasis box="[731,1020,1017,1043]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Anthernanthera maritima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1035,1213,1017,1044]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Amaranthaceae</taxonomicName>
) at Long Key State Park in southern Florida.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="207" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,153,1151]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1089,1115]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Etymology</emphasis>
. The genus name is close to, but not quite, an anagram of the related 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1967" box="[1119,1247,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spinipogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1119,1247,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Spinipogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and is feminine in gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
